│                                                                               │
│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                                   │
│                                                                               │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                               │
│ 1. Understanding the Issue:                                                   │
│ The crash occurs due to an assertion in BoUpSLP::newTreeEntry that rejects    │
│ reshuffling scalars for nodes with padding unless the vector length is a      │
│ power of two or full vectors are used. In this reproducer, the SLP builds a   │
│ node for a bundle of fcmp instructions (%cmp13.us and %cmp14.us), detects     │
│ reused scalars, and then hits the assertion because the element type used to  │
│ check hasFullVectorsOrPowerOf2 is invalid (x86_fp80). This makes the pass     │
│ think it is a padded/non-power-of-two case and disallows reshuffling, causing │
│ the abort.                                                                    │
│                                                                               │
│ 2. Analyzing opt's Log:                                                       │
│ - The pass successfully creates a TreeEntry for PHIs and for a bundle of      │
│ select instructions returning i64 0.                                          │
│ - Next, it analyzes a bundle containing %cmp13.us (fcmp olt x86_fp80 ...).    │
│ The debug log says "Shuffle for reused scalars" and then immediately fails    │
│ the assertion at line 3711.                                                   │
│ - The assertion checks hasFullVectorsOrPowerOf2(*TTI,                         │
│ getValueType(VL.front()), VL.size()) || ReuseShuffleIndices.empty(). Here     │
│ VL.front() is the fcmp, but getValueType returns x86_fp80 due to              │
│ special-casing CmpInst to return operand type.                                │
│ - Since x86_fp80 is explicitly filtered out by isValidElementType,            │
│ hasFullVectorsOrPowerOf2 returns false and the assertion triggers even though │
│ the vector length is 4 (a power of two) and the actual element we would       │
│ vectorize is the compare result type (i1), which is valid.                    │
│                                                                               │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                       │
│ The helper getValueType(Value *V) is used throughout SLP to determine the     │
│ scalar element type when forming widened vector types and checking            │
│ legality/full-vector/power-of-two conditions. It currently special-cases      │
│ CmpInst to return the operand type (the type being compared), not the result  │
│ type. For this test, that operand type is x86_fp80, which is marked invalid   │
│ for vectorization by isValidElementType, even though the actual values being  │
│ grouped are the compare results (i1), which are valid elements.               │
│ As a consequence, the legality/padding checks use x86_fp80 rather than i1,    │
│ falsely concluding that the group requires padding and rejecting reshuffles.  │
│ This directly leads to the assertion in newTreeEntry when ReuseShuffleIndices │
│ is non-empty.                                                                 │
│                                                                               │
│ Therefore, the bug is the incorrect type choice for compare instructions in   │
│ getValueType. We must use the compare’s result type (V->getType()) for        │
│ vectorization element checks, not the operand type.                           │
│                                                                               │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s):                                                    │
│ - File: llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp                       │
│ - Lines: 247-254                                                              │
│ - Change getValueType(Value *V) to stop returning the compare operand type    │
│ for CmpInst, and instead return V->getType(). This aligns with what SLP is    │
│ actually vectorizing (the scalar results of instructions), ensures            │
│ isValidElementType and hasFullVectorsOrPowerOf2 see i1 for fcmp bundles, and  │
│ prevents the false padding determination.                                     │
│                                                                               │
│ Suggested replacement for the function body segment:                          │
│                                                                               │
│ static Type *getValueType(Value *V) {                                         │
│   if (auto *SI = dyn_cast<StoreInst>(V))                                      │
│     return SI->getValueOperand()->getType();                                  │
│   // For comparisons, use the result type (e.g., i1), not the operand type.   │
│   // This reflects the scalar element being vectorized and avoids             │
│ misclassifying                                                                │
│   // valid groups as having invalid element types.                            │
│   if (isa<CmpInst>(V))                                                        │
│     return V->getType();                                                      │
│   if (auto *IE = dyn_cast<InsertElementInst>(V))                              │
│     return IE->getOperand(1)->getType();                                      │
│   return V->getType();                                                        │
│ }                                                                             │
│                                                                               │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                │
│ By making getValueType return the compare’s result type for CmpInst,          │
│ hasFullVectorsOrPowerOf2 and related checks will see a valid element type     │
│ (i1) for the fcmp bundles. With VL.size()==4, the power-of-two condition      │
│ holds, so reshuffling reused scalars is allowed and the assertion will not    │
│ trigger. This fix targets the first transformation point’s incorrect analysis │
│ input, matches the pass’s intent, and should resolve the crash for this and   │
│ similar cases involving comparisons on unsupported operand types (like        │
│ x86_fp80) while vectorizing their boolean results.                            │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                               │
