  "reason_thou": "1. Understanding the Issue:\nThe crash occurs due to an
assertion in BoUpSLP::newTreeEntry that rejects reshuffling scalars for nodes
with padding unless the vector length is a power of two or full vectors are used.
In this reproducer, the SLP builds a node for a bundle of fcmp instructions
(%cmp13.us and %cmp14.us), detects reused scalars, and then hits the assertion
because the element type used to check hasFullVectorsOrPowerOf2 is invalid
(x86_fp80). This makes the pass think it is a padded/non-power-of-two case and
disallows reshuffling, causing the abort.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\n- The pass
successfully creates a TreeEntry for PHIs and for a bundle of select instructions
returning i64 0.\n- Next, it analyzes a bundle containing %cmp13.us (fcmp olt
x86_fp80 ...). The debug log says \"Shuffle for reused scalars\" and then
immediately fails the assertion at line 3711.\n- The assertion checks
hasFullVectorsOrPowerOf2(*TTI, getValueType(VL.front()), VL.size()) ||
ReuseShuffleIndices.empty(). Here VL.front() is the fcmp, but getValueType
returns x86_fp80 due to special-casing CmpInst to return operand type.\n- Since
x86_fp80 is explicitly filtered out by isValidElementType,
hasFullVectorsOrPowerOf2 returns false and the assertion triggers even though the
vector length is 4 (a power of two) and the actual element we would vectorize is
the compare result type (i1), which is valid.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nThe
helper getValueType(Value *V) is used throughout SLP to determine the scalar
element type when forming widened vector types and checking
legality/full-vector/power-of-two conditions. It currently special-cases CmpInst
to return the operand type (the type being compared), not the result type. For
this test, that operand type is x86_fp80, which is marked invalid for
vectorization by isValidElementType, even though the actual values being grouped
are the compare results (i1), which are valid elements.\nAs a consequence, the
legality/padding checks use x86_fp80 rather than i1, falsely concluding that the
group requires padding and rejecting reshuffles. This directly leads to the
assertion in newTreeEntry when ReuseShuffleIndices is non-empty.\n\nTherefore,
the bug is the incorrect type choice for compare instructions in getValueType. We
must use the compare\u2019s result type (V->getType()) for vectorization element
checks, not the operand type.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\n- File:
llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp\n- Lines: 247-254\n- Change
getValueType(Value *V) to stop returning the compare operand type for CmpInst,
and instead return V->getType(). This aligns with what SLP is actually
vectorizing (the scalar results of instructions), ensures isValidElementType and
hasFullVectorsOrPowerOf2 see i1 for fcmp bundles, and prevents the false padding
determination.\n\nSuggested replacement for the function body segment:\n\nstatic
Type *getValueType(Value *V) {\n  if (auto *SI = dyn_cast<StoreInst>(V))\n
return SI->getValueOperand()->getType();\n  // For comparisons, use the result
type (e.g., i1), not the operand type.\n  // This reflects the scalar element
being vectorized and avoids misclassifying\n  // valid groups as having invalid
element types.\n  if (isa<CmpInst>(V))\n    return V->getType();\n  if (auto *IE
= dyn_cast<InsertElementInst>(V))\n    return IE->getOperand(1)->getType();\n
return V->getType();\n}\n\n5. Conclusion:\nBy making getValueType return the
compare\u2019s result type for CmpInst, hasFullVectorsOrPowerOf2 and related
checks will see a valid element type (i1) for the fcmp bundles. With
VL.size()==4, the power-of-two condition holds, so reshuffling reused scalars is
allowed and the assertion will not trigger. This fix targets the first
transformation point\u2019s incorrect analysis input, matches the pass\u2019s
intent, and should resolve the crash for this and similar cases involving
comparisons on unsupported operand types (like x86_fp80) while vectorizing their
boolean results.",
